{"questionId":"27905","questionHtml":"<p>An electrical circuit contains a capacitor. The charge on the capacitor, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math> Coulombs, at time&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds, satisfies the differential equation</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mo>d</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Initially&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Use Euler’s method with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math> to estimate the maximum charge on the capacitor during&nbsp;the first second.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>q</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>q</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msub></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msup><mo>d</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>y</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>q</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>q</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>y</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msub><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>q</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mo>d</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>q</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>evidence of using Euler’s method (e.g.)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/9f4e96dd61a3a8389ff06a68e1fe81ba7ea1d49e.png\"></p>\n<p>maximum charge&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;(Coulombs, at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A2</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A0A1</strong> </em>for a final answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math>, from reading the value at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27905","referenceCode":"22N.1.AHL.TZ0.15","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"An electrical circuit contains a capacitor. The charge on the capacitor, q Coulombs, at time t seconds, satisfies the differential equation d2qdt2+5dqdt+20q=200. Initially q=1 and ","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"15","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.18—Eulers method for 2nd order DEs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}